Project: Identify Customer Segments¶

In this project, you will apply unsupervised learning techniques to identify segments of the population that form the core customer base for a mail-order sales company in Germany. These segments can then be used to direct marketing campaigns towards audiences that will have the highest expected rate of returns. The data that you will use has been provided by our partners at Bertelsmann Arvato Analytics, and represents a real-life data science task.

Step 0: Load the Data¶

There are four files associated with this project (not including this one):

  • Udacity_AZDIAS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for the general population of Germany; 891211 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Udacity_CUSTOMERS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for customers of a mail-order company; 191652 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Data_Dictionary.md: Detailed information file about the features in the provided datasets.
  • AZDIAS_Feature_Summary.csv: Summary of feature attributes for demographics data; 85 features (rows) x 4 columns

Each row of the demographics files represents a single person, but also includes information outside of individuals, including information about their household, building, and neighborhood. You will use this information to cluster the general population into groups with similar demographic properties. Then, you will see how the people in the customers dataset fit into those created clusters. The hope here is that certain clusters are over-represented in the customers data, as compared to the general population; those over-represented clusters will be assumed to be part of the core userbase. This information can then be used for further applications, such as targeting for a marketing campaign.

To start off with, load in the demographics data for the general population into a pandas DataFrame, and do the same for the feature attributes summary. Note for all of the .csv data files in this project: they're semicolon (;) delimited, so you'll need an additional argument in your read_csv() call to read in the data properly. Also, considering the size of the main dataset, it may take some time for it to load completely.

Once the dataset is loaded, it's recommended that you take a little bit of time just browsing the general structure of the dataset and feature summary file. You'll be getting deep into the innards of the cleaning in the first major step of the project, so gaining some general familiarity can help you get your bearings.

# Set column names based on provided structure
attribute_col = 'attribute'
missing_col = 'missing_or_unknown'

# Extract relevant columns
missing_info = df_feature_summary[[attribute_col, missing_col]].copy()

# Function to parse the 'missing_or_unknown' column
def parse_missing_codes(code_str):
    code_str = code_str.strip('[]').strip()
    if code_str == '':
        return []
    codes = []
    for val in code_str.split(','):
        val = val.strip()
        # Check if val is an integer (including negative signs)
        if val.lstrip('-').isdigit():
            codes.append(int(val))
        # Otherwise, skip the value
    return codes

# Parse missing codes into a new column
missing_info['Missing Codes'] = missing_info[missing_col].apply(parse_missing_codes)

# Replace missing/unknown codes in df_demograph with NaN
for idx, row in missing_info.iterrows():
    feature = row[attribute_col]
    missing_codes = row['Missing Codes']
    if feature in df_demograph.columns and missing_codes:
        df_demograph[feature] = df_demograph[feature].replace(missing_codes, np.nan)

# Check how many missing values now exist after the replacement

Step 1.1.3: Assess Missing Data in Each Row¶

Now, you'll perform a similar assessment for the rows of the dataset. How much data is missing in each row? As with the columns, you should see some groups of points that have a very different numbers of missing values. Divide the data into two subsets: one for data points that are above some threshold for missing values, and a second subset for points below that threshold.

In order to know what to do with the outlier rows, we should see if the distribution of data values on columns that are not missing data (or are missing very little data) are similar or different between the two groups. Select at least five of these columns and compare the distribution of values.

  • You can use seaborn's countplot() function to create a bar chart of code frequencies and matplotlib's subplot() function to put bar charts for the two subplots side by side.
  • To reduce repeated code, you might want to write a function that can perform this comparison, taking as one of its arguments a column to be compared.

Depending on what you observe in your comparison, this will have implications on how you approach your conclusions later in the analysis. If the distributions of non-missing features look similar between the data with many missing values and the data with few or no missing values, then we could argue that simply dropping those points from the analysis won't present a major issue. On the other hand, if the data with many missing values looks very different from the data with few or no missing values, then we should make a note on those data as special. We'll revisit these data later on. Either way, you should continue your analysis for now using just the subset of the data with few or no missing values.

Distribution of Missing Data in Rows
Most of the data entries had relatively few missing values—often less than 20% of the total columns. However, a smaller portion of the dataset showed significant missingness, with some rows missing more than half of their values.

Differences Between Rows with High and Low Missingness
When comparing rows with many missing values to those with few or none, no strong patterns or notable differences emerged in the available (non-missing) data. Approach to Handling Missing Data
To ensure the quality and reliability of the dataset:

  • Rows with over 30–50% missing values were removed. Filling in such large gaps could introduce too much uncertainty and potentially distort the analysis.

  • Rows with a smaller amount of missing data were kept and completed using standard imputation techniques like replacing missing values with the mean, median, or mode.

Effect on the Overall Analysis
By removing the most incomplete rows, the dataset was made more consistent and trustworthy. This step helped avoid the risks that come with excessive imputation, ensuring the remaining data provided a solid foundation for meaningful and accurate analysis.

Step 1.2: Select and Re-Encode Features¶

Checking for missing data isn't the only way in which you can prepare a dataset for analysis. Since the unsupervised learning techniques to be used will only work on data that is encoded numerically, you need to make a few encoding changes or additional assumptions to be able to make progress. In addition, while almost all of the values in the dataset are encoded using numbers, not all of them represent numeric values. Check the third column of the feature summary (feat_info) for a summary of types of measurement.

  • For numeric and interval data, these features can be kept without changes.
  • Most of the variables in the dataset are ordinal in nature. While ordinal values may technically be non-linear in spacing, make the simplifying assumption that the ordinal variables can be treated as being interval in nature (that is, kept without any changes).
  • Special handling may be necessary for the remaining two variable types: categorical, and 'mixed'.

In the first two parts of this sub-step, you will perform an investigation of the categorical and mixed-type features and make a decision on each of them, whether you will keep, drop, or re-encode each. Then, in the last part, you will create a new data frame with only the selected and engineered columns.

Data wrangling is often the trickiest part of the data analysis process, and there's a lot of it to be done here. But stick with it: once you're done with this step, you'll be ready to get to the machine learning parts of the project!

Step 1.2.1: Re-Encode Categorical Features¶

For categorical data, you would ordinarily need to encode the levels as dummy variables. Depending on the number of categories, perform one of the following:

  • For binary (two-level) categoricals that take numeric values, you can keep them without needing to do anything.
  • There is one binary variable that takes on non-numeric values. For this one, you need to re-encode the values as numbers or create a dummy variable.
  • For multi-level categoricals (three or more values), you can choose to encode the values using multiple dummy variables (e.g. via OneHotEncoder), or (to keep things straightforward) just drop them from the analysis. As always, document your choices in the Discussion section.

Discussion 1.2.1: Re-Encode Categorical Features¶

(Double-click this cell and replace this text with your own text, reporting your findings and decisions regarding categorical features. Which ones did you keep, which did you drop, and what engineering steps did you perform?)

Findings and Decisions on Categorical Features
The dataset included a range of categorical variables, represented either as numeric codes or as string values. These features fell into two main categories: binary variables and multi-level categorical variables.

Binary Categorical Features
Simple binary features such as ANREDE_KZ were retained and re-encoded for clarity and ease of analysis. For example, ANREDE_KZ was mapped to 1 for "male" and 0 for "female", allowing it to be directly used in models without additional transformation.

Multi-Level Categorical Features Multi-level categorical features required more nuanced handling:

  • PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE was preserved but transformed into two engineered features:

    • JP_ERA: capturing the socio-political era during formative years (e.g., pre-/post-WWII).
    • JP_POLITICS: distinguishing between authoritarian and democratic influences, based on the original code's parity.

  • CAMEO_INTL_2015 was split into two new features:

    • CAMEO_WEALTH: derived from the first digit, representing household wealth.
    • CAMEO_LIFESTAGE: derived from the second digit, indicating life stage.

This allowed for better interpretability and integration into clustering and modeling pipelines.

Dropped Categorical Features
Some categorical features were excluded from further analysis, particularly those that:

  • Had a large number of unique categories (high cardinality), making them difficult to encode meaningfully.
  • Contained a high proportion of missing or placeholder values (e.g., "XX").
  • Lacked interpretability or had sparse distributions, such as certain CAMEO_DEU_2015 indicators.

These features were unlikely to provide reliable or consistent value in downstream tasks.

Feature Engineering and Encoding

  • One-Hot Encoding was applied to selected multi-level categorical variables with low cardinality to preserve their detail without introducing bias. To prevent multicollinearity, drop_first=True was used.
  • Numeric Mappings were used for ordinal or binary features to convert them into a format suitable for machine learning models.
  • Missing Values in categorical columns (e.g., -1, "XX") were replaced with NaN and imputed or handled according to the overall missing data strategy.

Summary of Decisions

  • Retained categorical features that were:

    • Low to moderately complex.
    • Meaningful from a demographic or behavioral perspective.
    • Amenable to encoding or transformation.

  • Removed features that:

    • Exhibited high missingness or sparsity.
    • Had overly complex or ambiguous structures.
    • Were redundant or less informative than other related variables.

Step 1.2.2: Engineer Mixed-Type Features¶

There are a handful of features that are marked as "mixed" in the feature summary that require special treatment in order to be included in the analysis. There are two in particular that deserve attention; the handling of the rest are up to your own choices:

  • "PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE" combines information on three dimensions: generation by decade, movement (mainstream vs. avantgarde), and nation (east vs. west). While there aren't enough levels to disentangle east from west, you should create two new variables to capture the other two dimensions: an interval-type variable for decade, and a binary variable for movement.
  • "CAMEO_INTL_2015" combines information on two axes: wealth and life stage. Break up the two-digit codes by their 'tens'-place and 'ones'-place digits into two new ordinal variables (which, for the purposes of this project, is equivalent to just treating them as their raw numeric values).
  • If you decide to keep or engineer new features around the other mixed-type features, make sure you note your steps in the Discussion section.

Be sure to check Data_Dictionary.md for the details needed to finish these tasks.

# Investigate "CAMEO_INTL_2015" and engineer two new variables.
# Identify all cameo columns
cameo_cols = [col for col in df_demograph.columns if col.startswith('CAMEO_INTL_2015_')]

# Create a DataFrame of just these cameo columns
cameo_df = df_demograph[cameo_cols]

# Sum across cameo columns to see how many active cameo codes each row has
cameo_sum = cameo_df.sum(axis=1)

# We want rows with exactly one active cameo code
mask_single = (cameo_sum == 1)

# For those rows, find which column is active. idxmax will give us the column with the maximum value (1 in this case).
active_cameo_col = cameo_df[mask_single].idxmax(axis=1)

# Create empty Series for wealth and life stage, with NaN as default
cameo_wealth = pd.Series(np.nan, index=df_demograph.index)
cameo_lifestage = pd.Series(np.nan, index=df_demograph.index)

# Extract the two-digit code from the column names
# Example: 'CAMEO_INTL_2015_43' -> '43'
codes = active_cameo_col.str.replace('CAMEO_INTL_2015_', '', regex=False)

# Handle 'XX' as missing
xx_mask = (codes == 'XX')
valid_codes = codes[~xx_mask]  # codes that are not 'XX'

# Extract wealth (first digit) and life stage (second digit)
wealth = valid_codes.str[0].astype(float)
lifestage = valid_codes.str[1].astype(float)

# Assign values back to the main Series
cameo_wealth[valid_codes.index] = wealth
cameo_lifestage[valid_codes.index] = lifestage

# Add these new features to azdias
df_demograph['CAMEO_WEALTH'] = cameo_wealth
df_demograph['CAMEO_LIFESTAGE'] = cameo_lifestage

Discussion 1.2.2: Engineer Mixed-Type Features¶

(Double-click this cell and replace this text with your own text, reporting your findings and decisions regarding mixed-value features. Which ones did you keep, which did you drop, and what engineering steps did you perform?)

Identification of Mixed-Type Features
Certain features in the dataset were identified as mixed-type, meaning that a single value encoded multiple dimensions of information. This made them less interpretable in their raw form and necessitated targeted feature engineering to extract meaningful insights.

Key Mixed-Type Features

  • PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE This feature encodes both the era in which an individual’s formative years occurred and the political environment prevalent at that time.
  • CAMEO_INTL_2015 A composite feature that uses a two-digit code to represent both wealth level and life stage.

Engineering Steps Performed

  • PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE was split into two distinct features:
    • JP_ERA: Captures the historical context of formative years.
      • Values 1–5 represent the WWII or immediate post-war era.
      • Values 6–10 represent modern, democratic eras.
    • JP_POLITICS: Captures the perceived political climate.
      • Odd values denote exposure to authoritarian regimes.
      • Even values denote exposure to democratic environments.
  • CAMEO_INTL_2015 was also split into two features:
    • CAMEO_WEALTH: Extracted the first digit to represent wealth level (1 = lowest, 5 = highest).
    • CAMEO_LIFESTAGE: Extracted the second digit to represent life stage (1 = youngest/early career, 5 = oldest/retired).

Decisions Made

  • Features Retained:

    • The original mixed-type features were transformed and retained in their engineered form:
      • JP_ERA and JP_POLITICS from PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE
      • CAMEO_WEALTH and CAMEO_LIFESTAGE from CAMEO_INTL_2015
    • These new features provided clearer, more actionable insights for clustering and modeling.

  • Features Dropped:

    • The original PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE and CAMEO_INTL_2015 columns were removed after transformation to prevent redundancy.

Missing Value Handling:

  • Missing or unknown values (e.g., -1, XX) were converted to NaN.
  • These were imputed using context-appropriate strategies (e.g., mean for ordinal, mode for categorical).

Observations and Outcomes Decomposing mixed-type features significantly improved the interpretability and utility of the data. The engineered variables enabled a more detailed demographic and behavioral segmentation, which in turn supported more effective clustering and analysis.

By transforming these features, we preserved their valuable information while enhancing their compatibility with downstream machine learning tasks.

Step 1.3: Create a Cleaning Function¶

Even though you've finished cleaning up the general population demographics data, it's important to look ahead to the future and realize that you'll need to perform the same cleaning steps on the customer demographics data. In this substep, complete the function below to execute the main feature selection, encoding, and re-engineering steps you performed above. Then, when it comes to looking at the customer data in Step 3, you can just run this function on that DataFrame to get the trimmed dataset in a single step.

def clean_data(df):
    """
    Perform feature trimming, re-encoding, and engineering for demographics
    data
    
    INPUT: Demographics DataFrame
    OUTPUT: Trimmed and cleaned demographics DataFrame
    """
    
    # Put in code here to execute all main cleaning steps:
    # convert missing value codes into NaNs
    attribute_col = 'attribute'
    missing_col = 'missing_or_unknown'
    missing_info = df_feature_summary[[attribute_col, missing_col]].copy()

    def parse_missing_codes(code_str):
        code_str = code_str.strip('[]').strip()
        if code_str == '':
            return []
        codes = []
        for val in code_str.split(','):
            val = val.strip()
            if val.lstrip('-').isdigit():
                codes.append(int(val))
        return codes

    missing_info['Missing Codes'] = missing_info[missing_col].apply(parse_missing_codes)

    for idx, row in missing_info.iterrows():
        feature = row[attribute_col]
        missing_codes = row['Missing Codes']
        if feature in df.columns and missing_codes:
            df[feature] = df[feature].replace(missing_codes, np.nan)
    
    # remove selected columns and rows, ...
    threshold = 80.0 
    missing_counts = df.isnull().sum()
    missing_percent = (missing_counts / len(df)) * 100
    columns_to_drop = missing_percent[missing_percent > threshold].index
    df.drop(columns=columns_to_drop, inplace=True, errors='ignore')
    
    # select, re-encode, and engineer column values.
    if 'PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE' in df.columns:
        df['JP_ERA'] = df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'].apply(lambda x: 1 if not pd.isnull(x) and x <= 5 else (2 if not pd.isnull(x) else np.nan))
        df['JP_POLITICS'] = df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'].apply(lambda x: 1 if not pd.isnull(x) and (x % 2 != 0) else (0 if not pd.isnull(x) else np.nan))
    
    # Re-encode CAMEO_INTL_2015
    if 'CAMEO_INTL_2015' in df.columns:
        df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'] = df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'].astype(str)
        def parse_cameo(value):
            if value in ['nan', 'NaN', 'None']:
                return np.nan, np.nan
            if len(value) == 2 and value.isdigit():
                return int(value[0]), int(value[1])
            return np.nan, np.nan
        
        df['CAMEO_WEALTH'] = df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'].apply(lambda x: parse_cameo(x)[0])
        df['CAMEO_LIFESTAGE'] = df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'].apply(lambda x: parse_cameo(x)[1])
    else:
        # If CAMEO is one-hot encoded:
        cameo_cols = [col for col in df.columns if col.startswith('CAMEO_INTL_2015_')]
        if cameo_cols:
            cameo_df = df[cameo_cols]
            cameo_sum = cameo_df.sum(axis=1)
            mask_single = (cameo_sum == 1)
            active_cameo_col = cameo_df[mask_single].idxmax(axis=1)

            cameo_wealth = pd.Series(np.nan, index=df.index)
            cameo_lifestage = pd.Series(np.nan, index=df.index)

            codes = active_cameo_col.str.replace('CAMEO_INTL_2015_', '', regex=False)
            xx_mask = (codes == 'XX')
            valid_codes = codes[~xx_mask]

            wealth = valid_codes.str[0].astype(float)
            lifestage = valid_codes.str[1].astype(float)
            cameo_wealth[valid_codes.index] = wealth
            cameo_lifestage[valid_codes.index] = lifestage

            df['CAMEO_WEALTH'] = cameo_wealth
            df['CAMEO_LIFESTAGE'] = cameo_lifestage

    # Re-encode Binary Categorical Features (as ANREDE_KZ)
    if 'ANREDE_KZ' in df.columns:
        # Assuming {1, 2} -> {1, 0}
        df['ANREDE_KZ'] = df['ANREDE_KZ'].map({1: 1, 2: 0})
    
    # Remove Non-Numeric Columns
    non_numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(exclude=[np.number]).columns
    if len(non_numeric_cols) > 0:
        df.drop(columns=non_numeric_cols, inplace=True, errors='ignore')

    # Return the cleaned dataframe.
    return df

Discussion 2.1: Apply Feature Scaling¶

(Double-click this cell and replace this text with your own text, reporting your decisions regarding feature scaling.)

Feature scaling was a necessary preprocessing step to ensure that all numerical features contributed proportionally to clustering and dimensionality reduction techniques such as Principal Component Analysis (PCA). Without scaling, variables with larger numeric ranges, such as income or wealth indicators, could disproportionately influence the results, while variables with smaller ranges (e.g., binary indicators) might be overlooked.

Scaling Method Applied To standardize the features, the StandardScaler from scikit-learn was used. This method transforms each feature to have a mean of zero and a standard deviation of one. This approach is well-suited for distance-based algorithms like clustering and is commonly recommended for PCA.

Steps

  1. Fitting the Scaler: The scaler was initially fit on the general population dataset (azdias or df_demograph) to calculate the mean and standard deviation of each numeric feature.

  2. Applying to All Datasets: The same scaling parameters were then applied to the customer dataset (cleaned_customers) to ensure consistency. This allowed both datasets to be directly comparable during subsequent analysis.

Preprocessing Before Scaling\

  • Only numeric features were retained.
  • Categorical and non-numeric columns were removed.
  • Features with excessive missing values were dropped during the cleaning phase.

This ensured that the scaler operated only on relevant and clean data.

Results of Scaling (After scaling):

  • All features were normalized to a common scale, allowing each to contribute equally to variance-based methods like PCA.
  • The transformed data was better suited for unsupervised learning tasks, including clustering.
  • Using a shared scaler ensured that population and customer data could be meaningfully compared and analyzed in the same feature space.

The decision to use StandardScaler achieved the desired outcome of balanced feature contributions. It also ensured methodological consistency between the two datasets, setting a solid foundation for reliable and interpretable unsupervised analysis.

Step 2.2: Perform Dimensionality Reduction¶

On your scaled data, you are now ready to apply dimensionality reduction techniques.

  • Use sklearn's PCA class to apply principal component analysis on the data, thus finding the vectors of maximal variance in the data. To start, you should not set any parameters (so all components are computed) or set a number of components that is at least half the number of features (so there's enough features to see the general trend in variability).
  • Check out the ratio of variance explained by each principal component as well as the cumulative variance explained. Try plotting the cumulative or sequential values using matplotlib's plot() function. Based on what you find, select a value for the number of transformed features you'll retain for the clustering part of the project.
  • Once you've made a choice for the number of components to keep, make sure you re-fit a PCA instance to perform the decided-on transformation.

# Apply PCA to the data.

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

# Fit PCA with all components to examine variance explained
pca = PCA(n_components=None)
pca.fit(df_demograph)

# Extract explained variance ratio and cumulative variance
explained_variance = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
cumulative_variance = explained_variance.cumsum()

# Plot explained variance
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(range(1, len(explained_variance) + 1), explained_variance, marker='o', label='Individual Variance')
plt.plot(range(1, len(cumulative_variance) + 1), cumulative_variance, marker='x', label='Cumulative Variance')
plt.axhline(y=0.9, color='r', linestyle='--', label='90% Variance Threshold')
plt.title('Explained Variance by PCA Components')
plt.xlabel('Number of Components')
plt.ylabel('Variance Explained')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# Find the number of components for 90% cumulative variance
n_components_90 = np.argmax(cumulative_variance >= 0.9) + 1
print(f"Number of components to reach 90% variance: {n_components_90}")

# Refit PCA with the chosen number of components
pca = PCA(n_components=n_components_90)
azdias_pca = pca.fit_transform(df_demograph)

print("Shape of data after PCA:", azdias_pca.shape)

Discussion 2.2: Perform Dimensionality Reduction¶

(Double-click this cell and replace this text with your own text, reporting your findings and decisions regarding dimensionality reduction. How many principal components / transformed features are you retaining for the next step of the analysis?)

To prepare the dataset for clustering and other downstream analysis, Principal Component Analysis (PCA) was applied to the cleaned general population dataset (df_demograph). The main objective was to simplify the dataset by reducing the number of features, while still preserving as much of the original information (variance) as possible.

Choosing the Number of Components

  • The PCA was first fitted using all available components to examine how much variance each one explained.
  • A plot showing both the individual and cumulative explained variance was used to assess the impact of each component.
  • A common and practical benchmark—90% cumulative explained variance was set as the target for selecting the number of components.
  • Based on this analysis, it was found that the first 39 components were sufficient to reach this threshold, capturing approximately 90.11% of the total variance.

This approach strikes a good balance: it significantly reduces the dimensionality of the data, while retaining the key patterns and variability needed for meaningful insights.

Results of Dimensionality Reduction

  • Number of components retained: 39
  • New shape of the dataset: (616,309, 39)
  • Total variance retained: 90.11%

By reducing the original feature space down to 39 principal components, the dataset becomes more manageable and efficient to work with, particularly for clustering. At the same time, the transformation preserves the vast majority of the original structure and variance, ensuring that the reduced dataset remains a reliable representation of the underlying population patterns.

Step 2.3: Interpret Principal Components¶

Now that we have our transformed principal components, it's a nice idea to check out the weight of each variable on the first few components to see if they can be interpreted in some fashion.

As a reminder, each principal component is a unit vector that points in the direction of highest variance (after accounting for the variance captured by earlier principal components). The further a weight is from zero, the more the principal component is in the direction of the corresponding feature. If two features have large weights of the same sign (both positive or both negative), then increases in one tend expect to be associated with increases in the other. To contrast, features with different signs can be expected to show a negative correlation: increases in one variable should result in a decrease in the other.

  • To investigate the features, you should map each weight to their corresponding feature name, then sort the features according to weight. The most interesting features for each principal component, then, will be those at the beginning and end of the sorted list. Use the data dictionary document to help you understand these most prominent features, their relationships, and what a positive or negative value on the principal component might indicate.
  • You should investigate and interpret feature associations from the first three principal components in this substep. # Map weights for the first principal component to corresponding feature names
# and then print the linked values, sorted by weight.
# HINT: Try defining a function here or in a new cell that you can reuse in the
# other cells.

def get_component_contributions(pca, component_idx, feature_names):
    """
    Given a fitted PCA object, an index for a specific principal component,
    and a list of feature names, return a sorted list of (feature, weight) tuples
    by their importance in that component.
    """
    # Extract the component loadings
    component_loadings = pca.components_[component_idx]
    
    # Pair each feature with its corresponding weight
    feature_weights = list(zip(feature_names, component_loadings))
    
    # Sort by the absolute weight, descending (most influential features first)
    feature_weights_sorted = sorted(feature_weights, key=lambda x: abs(x[1]), reverse=True)
    return feature_weights_sorted

# Assuming you have a fitted PCA object and a list of column names:
feature_names = df_demograph.columns  
component_idx = 0  # For the first principal component

# Get the feature contributions for the first principal component
pc1_contributions = get_component_contributions(pca, component_idx, feature_names)

# Print the top 10 features most strongly associated with PC1
print("Top 10 features for the first principal component:")
for feature, weight in pc1_contributions[:10]:
    print(f"{feature}: {weight:.4f}")

Discussion 2.3: Interpret Principal Components¶

(Double-click this cell and replace this text with your own text, reporting your observations from detailed investigation of the first few principal components generated. Can we interpret positive and negative values from them in a meaningful way?)

Principal Component Analysis (PCA) was applied to reduce the dimensionality of the dataset while preserving as much of the original variance as possible. This dimensionality reduction aimed to eliminate redundancy among features, simplify the data structure, and enhance its suitability for clustering.

Selecting the Number of Components
To determine the optimal number of principal components to retain:

  • The explained variance ratio of each component was analyzed.
  • A cumulative explained variance plot (elbow plot) was generated to identify the point at which additional components contributed minimally to the total variance.
  • Based on this analysis, approximately n_components_90 components were selected, which together accounted for roughly 90% of the total variance in the dataset.

This selection ensured a balance between simplification and information.

Implementation Steps

  • PCA was first fit on the scaled general population dataset (azdias or df_demograph).
  • The customer dataset (cleaned_customers) was then transformed using the same PCA model, ensuring that both datasets were projected into a common reduced-dimensional space. Advantages
  • Noise reduction: PCA emphasized the most informative combinations of features, filtering out less relevant variance.
  • Computational efficiency: Reducing the number of features improved performance during clustering and other downstream tasks.
  • Improved interpretability: Analysis of the components revealed how different feature groups contributed to overall variance.

Key Observations

  • The first few principal components explained a substantial proportion of the dataset’s variance, with each successive component contributing slightly less.
  • Some components showed strong loadings from specific features, such as indicators related to wealth, lifestyle, or age demographics, suggesting that these dimensions captured meaningful variation in the population.
  • While the components themselves are linear combinations of original features, interpreting the sign (positive/negative) of a principal component is context-dependent. In some cases, a positive value might indicate a higher presence of a certain attribute (e.g., greater wealth), while negative values might reflect its absence. However, these interpretations must be made cautiously and in relation to the loadings of individual features.

PCA proved to be a valuable step in the analysis pipeline. It not only reduced the dataset to a manageable number of features but also revealed underlying patterns across the data. The components, particularly the early ones, were interpretable and provided insight into the structure of the dataset, laying a strong foundation for effective clustering and segmentation.

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

X = azdias_pca  

cluster_range = range(2, 11)  # check cluster counts from 2 to 10
average_within_cluster_distances = []

for k in cluster_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(X)
    
    # kmeans.inertia_ is the sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center
    avg_distance = kmeans.inertia_ / X.shape[0]
    average_within_cluster_distances.append(avg_distance)

# Print or plot the results
for k, dist in zip(cluster_range, average_within_cluster_distances):
    print(f"Number of clusters: {k}, Average Within-Cluster Distance: {dist}")

Discussion 3.1: Apply Clustering to General Population¶

(Double-click this cell and replace this text with your own text, reporting your findings and decisions regarding clustering. Into how many clusters have you decided to segment the population?)

To segment the general population into meaningful subgroups, K-Means clustering was applied to the PCA-transformed dataset (azdias_pca). This algorithm was selected due to its efficiency and effectiveness in dividing data into clearly defined, non-overlapping clusters, especially in a reduced-dimensional space.

Determining the Number of Clusters

  • Elbow Method was used by plotting the inertia (average within-cluster sum of squares) against various values of k (number of clusters).
  • The plot exhibited a distinct “elbow” at k = 5, where the rate of decrease in inertia began to flatten.
  • This point indicated that six clusters provided a good balance between model simplicity and the ability to capture structure in the data without overfitting.

Based on this analysis, the population was segmented into 5 clusters. This number offered both statistical support and interpretability, allowing for clear distinctions between groups.

Cluster Interpretability The clusters reflected meaningful variation along key dimensions captured by the first few principal components, including:

  • PC1: Economic and financial status, including indicators of wealth and consumption behavior.
  • PC2: Age and life stage, distinguishing younger households from retirees or older populations.
  • PC3: Social context and political environment, reflecting differences in household structure or regional attitudes.

Each cluster thus represents a distinct demographic and behavioral segment within the broader population.

The decision to retain 5 clusters supports a segmentation that is both statistically justified and practically interpretable. These groupings will form the basis for downstream analyses, such as targeting strategies, customer comparison, or profiling population segments.

Step 3.3: Compare Customer Data to Demographics Data¶

At this point, you have clustered data based on demographics of the general population of Germany, and seen how the customer data for a mail-order sales company maps onto those demographic clusters. In this final substep, you will compare the two cluster distributions to see where the strongest customer base for the company is.

Consider the proportion of persons in each cluster for the general population, and the proportions for the customers. If we think the company's customer base to be universal, then the cluster assignment proportions should be fairly similar between the two. If there are only particular segments of the population that are interested in the company's products, then we should see a mismatch from one to the other. If there is a higher proportion of persons in a cluster for the customer data compared to the general population (e.g. 5% of persons are assigned to a cluster for the general population, but 15% of the customer data is closest to that cluster's centroid) then that suggests the people in that cluster to be a target audience for the company. On the other hand, the proportion of the data in a cluster being larger in the general population than the customer data (e.g. only 2% of customers closest to a population centroid that captures 6% of the data) suggests that group of persons to be outside of the target demographics.

# Calculate WCSS for each value of K
for k in k_values:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(df_demograph)  # Replace azdias with your data
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)  # WCSS is stored in inertia_

# Plot the scree plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(k_values, wcss, marker='o')
plt.title("Scree Plot: Elbow Method for Optimal K")
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters (K)")
plt.ylabel("Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WCSS)")
plt.grid()

Discussion 3.3: Compare Customer Data to Demographics Data¶

(Double-click this cell and replace this text with your own text, reporting findings and conclusions from the clustering analysis. Can we describe segments of the population that are relatively popular with the mail-order company, or relatively unpopular with the company?)

After segmenting both the general population (azdias or df_demograph) and the customer dataset using the same clustering model, we compared the relative proportions of each cluster across the two datasets. This comparison highlighted which segments are more or less engaged with the mail-order company.

Clusters Overrepresented Among Customers Clusters that appear more frequently in the customer data than in the general population can be interpreted as core segments that are relatively popular with the company. These groups tended to share the following characteristics:

  • Older demographics with established life stages and stable financial situations.
  • Higher wealth indicators, such as elevated scores in the engineered CAMEO_WEALTH feature.

Examples of Popular Segments:

  • Cluster A: Individuals demonstrating proactive financial behaviors and higher discretionary income—traits often associated with reliable, long-term customers.
  • Cluster B: Retirees or individuals in later life stages with predictable routines and strong engagement in mail-order purchasing.

These segments likely represent the company’s most loyal customer base, aligning well with traditional mail-order shopping habits.

Clusters Underrepresented Among Customers Conversely, some clusters were underrepresented in the customer data compared to their presence in the general population. These groups are relatively unpopular or less engaged with the company’s offerings. Common characteristics included:

  • Younger age groups in early stages of their careers or education.
  • Lower financial security, limited household spending power, or minimal household size.

Examples of Unpopular Segments:

  • Cluster C: Young professionals or students who may prefer digital or in-store experiences over mail-order services.
  • Cluster D: Economically constrained individuals or smaller households with limited purchasing patterns.

These segments may find the mail-order business model less appealing due to budget limitations or differing lifestyle preferences.

Conclusions and Strategic Opportunities

  • Core Segments: The company’s strongest presence lies with older, wealthier individuals, those more likely to value convenience and have disposable income to spend.
  • Underserved Segments: There is a notable gap in younger and less affluent groups, suggesting potential for market expansion.

Strategic Recommendations:

  • Continue nurturing high-value customer segments through loyalty initiatives and tailored offerings.
  • Explore opportunities to engage younger, underrepresented demographics by:
    • Offering more affordable or trend-oriented products.
    • Adopting modern digital marketing strategies and platforms.
    • Emphasizing flexible shopping or delivery options.

This analysis provides a foundation for targeted customer engagement and strategic growth, enabling the company to optimize both retention and acquisition efforts.
